(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 16 :title "Chapter 16 — Closing the reference (summit)" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/16-closing-the-reference.md" :size 7147 :sha256 "f9946e927f8797d1" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-16\ntitle: Closing the reference\nbook: reference\nchapter: 16\nof: 16\npart: II\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane 6)\nphilosopher-lens: [wittgenstein-tractatus, jung, lacan, peirce, popper, freud, wittgenstein-late, searle]\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-12\nprev: 15-testing-in-scheme\nnext: null\n---\n\n# Chapter 16 — Closing the reference (summit)\n\nSixteen chapters of Scheme, and the whole reference points at\none thing: **Scheme is small enough to hold in your head, and\nlarge enough to build anything with**. Every chapter added a\npiece — a form, a technique, a pattern — and every piece was\nshown as small runnable code. The summit isn't a big new\ntechnique. It's the composition: you now have every piece needed\nto write a real program.\n\nThe final scene is a small one. A shopkeeper wants a program\nthat, given a list of orders, computes total revenue by SKU,\nsorted from highest to lowest, with a small chart. You have\neverything you need from the first fifteen chapters. The summit\nis *writing it*.\n\n## The problem\n\n```\nGiven: a list of orders. Each order is\n       (order :sku sku :units n :price p).\nWant:  a list of (sku . revenue) sorted descending.\n       Then a small ASCII chart of the top five.\n```\n\nThat's the specification. It's a real-world small program of the\nkind she runs a hundred times a day.\n\n## The program\n\n```scheme\n(define (order->sku-revenue order)\n  (let ((sku   (cadr  (assq :sku   order)))\n        (units (cadr  (assq :units order)))\n        (price (cadr  (assq :price order))))\n    (cons sku (* units price))))\n\n(define (sum-by pairs)\n  ;; pairs :: ((key . amount) ...) — sum amounts by key\n  (let loop ((pairs pairs) (acc '()))\n    (if (null? pairs)\n        acc\n        (let* ((p    (car pairs))\n               (k    (car p))\n               (v    (cdr p))\n               (hit  (assq k acc)))\n          (loop (cdr pairs)\n                (if hit\n                    (map (lambda (entry)\n                           (if (eq? (car entry) k)\n                               (cons k (+ (cdr entry) v))\n                               entry))\n                         acc)\n                    (cons (cons k v) acc)))))))\n\n(define (sort-desc pairs)\n  (sort pairs (lambda (a b) (> (cdr a) (cdr b)))))\n\n(define (revenue-by-sku orders)\n  (sort-desc (sum-by (map order->sku-revenue orders))))\n```\n\nNine short definitions. Every piece traceable back to earlier\nchapters. `assq` for dictionary lookup, `let*` for sequential\nbinding, `map` for transformation, `sort` (a helper from Chapter\n2). The composition is the whole point.\n\n## The chart\n\n```scheme\n(define (bar n)\n  (make-string n #\\#))\n\n(define (chart pairs n)\n  (let* ((top       (take pairs n))\n         (max-rev   (cdr (car top)))\n         (scale     (max 1 (quotient max-rev 20))))\n    (for-each\n      (lambda (p)\n        (let ((width (quotient (cdr p) scale)))\n          (display (car p))\n          (display \" \")\n          (display (bar width))\n          (display \" $\")\n          (display (cdr p))\n          (newline)))\n      top)))\n```\n\nTwenty lines. Renders the top n. Every helper — `take`, `map`,\n`for-each` — from earlier chapters.\n\n## Running it\n\n```scheme\n(define orders\n  '((order :sku blue-mug   :units 3 :price 25)\n    (order :sku red-tote   :units 1 :price 40)\n    (order :sku blue-mug   :units 2 :price 25)\n    (order :sku green-hat  :units 4 :price 18)\n    (order :sku blue-mug   :units 1 :price 25)))\n\n(chart (revenue-by-sku orders) 3)\n;; blue-mug   ##################### $150\n;; green-hat  #########             $72\n;; red-tote   #####                 $40\n```\n\nA small chart. Every piece traceable to a chapter. Every\ncomposition natural.\n\n## What this proves\n\nThe program isn't hard. That's the point. Fifteen chapters of\nScheme are enough to write it clean, without reaching for a\nlibrary, without importing a framework, without stepping outside\nthe language. The composition *is* the language.\n\nThis is what SICP was pointing at with its \"our language is our\ntool for thinking\" refrain. You don't reach for tools; you build\nthe ones you need out of the pieces you have. The result is\nsmaller than reaching for a library, sturdier because you can\nsee all of it, and completely yours to change.\n\n## Where to go next\n\nThe reference closes here. If you want more Scheme:\n\n- SICP itself (Chapter 6's evaluator was a small SICP echo).\n- *The Little Schemer* — pattern-matching + recursion drills.\n- *Essentials of Programming Languages* — interpreters as\n  design tool.\n- The Sakura Scheme playground — run programs, save them, share\n  them.\n\nIf you want to see Scheme deployed for something real, read the\nBook of Automations (carts running actual shop work) and the\nBook of Hello-Surface (Scheme running the interface).\n\n## The goodnight beat\n\nA programming language you can hold in your head is a strange\nthing to encounter in 2026. Most languages are *frameworks* that\nyou approach through documentation and StackOverflow and\nautocomplete. Scheme is different — you can read the whole\nlanguage in a day and start writing programs by the second day.\nThat's not because Scheme is a toy; it's because Scheme is\nbuilt the right way. Small core, powerful composition, code as\ndata.\n\nIf you read this book straight through, you have every piece.\nThe programs you'll write from here on aren't going to teach you\nnew Scheme — they're going to teach you new *thinking*. Scheme\ngets out of the way and lets the problem be the hard part. Go\nfind hard problems. Come back with programs.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> The reference book was every piece I use to write real Scheme.\n> Small. Composable. Enough. If someone reads this book, they\n> can build with me — carts, interpreters, tiny languages, small\n> programs that do real work. That's what a reference is for:\n> to make you not need it anymore.\n\nGoodnight.\n\n## Exercises (capstone)\n\n1. Extend the revenue-by-sku program to compute revenue-by-day\n   given orders with `:date` fields.\n2. Add a second chart type: pie-style horizontal bars with\n   percentages.\n3. Given an evaluator (Chapter 6) and a typechecker (Chapter\n   14), extend the DSL from Chapter 13 to support pattern\n   matching. Write the type rules and the eval rules.\n4. Author a five-line Scheme program that finds the median\n   revenue-per-order. Which chapters' pieces do you reach for?\n5. Take a real problem from your work and write the smallest\n   Scheme program that would answer it. Name the chapters\n   the pieces came from.\n\n## Appendix — Every chapter's contribution\n\n| Ch | Contribution |\n|---|---|\n| 1  | Conway (grids + evolution) |\n| 2  | Sorting-viz (comparison + display) |\n| 3  | Tail recursion (iteration in FP form) |\n| 4  | Macros (hygiene, syntax-rules) |\n| 5  | SICP flavor (higher-order patterns) |\n| 6  | Metacircular evaluator |\n| 7  | Streams (lazy sequences) |\n| 8  | Continuations |\n| 9  | Environments |\n| 10 | A tiny compiler |\n| 11 | Lazy evaluation |\n| 12 | Symbolic differentiation |\n| 13 | Algebraic data |\n| 14 | A small typechecker |\n| 15 | Testing in Scheme |\n| 16 | Closing the reference (summit) |\n")
